# ACC Voices — scheduled batch pipeline (NOT an always-on service).
#
# Two cadences, two entry points. There are no webhooks, queues, or listeners:
# polling a few role inboxes + occasional transcripts is low-volume, and the
# urgent SLA is same-day, so polling is sufficient and far cheaper to operate.
# Urgent latency == the frequent-job interval below.
#
# Install with:  crontab cron/crontab.example
# (adjust paths / interpreter to your deployment)

# --- Frequent job: ingest - extract - grade - route ------------------------
# Early-morning + midday runs => an issue raised overnight escalates by morning,
# one raised in the morning escalates by midday. Comfortably same-day.
0 6  * * *  cd /opt/acc-voices && /usr/bin/python3 -m pipeline.entrypoints ingest_extract_triage >> /var/log/acc-voices/ingest.log 2>&1
0 12 * * *  cd /opt/acc-voices && /usr/bin/python3 -m pipeline.entrypoints ingest_extract_triage >> /var/log/acc-voices/ingest.log 2>&1

# --- Weekly job: aggregate - cluster - digest ------------------------------
# Monday 07:00: cluster the week's accumulated candidates and send the digest.
0 7  * * 1  cd /opt/acc-voices && /usr/bin/python3 -m pipeline.entrypoints aggregate_and_digest >> /var/log/acc-voices/digest.log 2>&1

# To tighten the urgent SLA, raise the frequency of the first job (e.g. every
# 3 hours). Only if the SLA ever drops to minutes would event-driven ingestion
# be worth considering — explicitly a deferred future option, not part of v1.
